The U.S. Anti-China Tech War
From New York — The worst diplomatic policy decision made by the previous generation (and even earlier generations) of Americans was the "War of Choice" launched against Iraq in 2003, which claimed the purpose was to eliminate — — allegedly non-existent — — weapons of mass destruction.
Understanding the necessity of the flawed logic behind this disastrous decision has become more critical than ever, as the same logic is now being used to justify similar U.S. misleading policies.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-U.S. Vice President Richard Cheney, who argued that even if the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands was small (for example, 1%), we should act as if it were certain to happen.
But this line of reasoning almost always leads to incorrect decisions.
However, the U.S. and some of its allies are now using "Cheneyism" to attack Chinese technology.
According to the U.S. government, since we cannot be certain that Chinese technology is safe, we should respond and suppress it as if it were necessarily harmful.
Correct decision-making would apply probability estimates to alternative courses of action.
A generation ago, U.S. policymakers should not only have considered the (claimed) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into terrorist hands, but also the 99% risk of waging a war based on multiple flawed assumptions.
By focusing solely on that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) distracted the public's attention, leading people to overlook the fact that the Iraq War lacked justification and would seriously destabilize Middle Eastern and global politics.
But the problem with the Cheney doctrine is not only that it forces action based on minor risks without considering the high potential costs, but that politicians always stir up fear for some undisclosed purposes.
This is exactly what U.S. leaders are doing again: by pointing out and exaggerating certain minor risks to incite panic about Chinese tech companies.
The case most relevant (but not the only one) is the U.S. government's attack on the telecommunications technology company Huawei.
The U.S. is gradually closing its domestic market to the company and striving to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the U.S. may ultimately cause an unfounded geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been following Huawei's technological progress, because I believe 5G and other digital technologies can provide a huge push toward achieving the Sustainable Development Goals, including the eradication of poverty.
I have also engaged in similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and encouraged the industry to enhance actions toward the Sustainable Development Goals.
I once wrote a short preface for a report Huawei had prepared on this topic (without payment), and as a result, I was criticized by those hostile to China. I then asked industry executives and government officials if there was evidence of any misconduct by Huawei, and the repeated answer was that Huawei's conduct was no different from that of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Nevertheless, the U.S. government still believes that Huawei's 5G equipment may endanger global security.
U.S. officials claim that "backdoors" in Huawei's software or hardware may allow the Chinese government to conduct surveillance worldwide.
They point out that Chinese law requires Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are clear now.
Huawei's 5G equipment is inexpensive and of high quality, currently leading many competitors and has already started to be rolled out.
Its high performance comes from years of substantial investment in R&D, scale economy effects, and Huawei's experience navigating the Chinese digital market.
Considering the importance of this technology for sustainable development, it would be clearly unwise for low-income economies around the world to refuse to adopt 5G early on.
However, despite the lack of any evidence of backdoors, the United States is still lobbying the world to distance itself from Huawei.
The U.S. argument is universal in nature.
As one U.S. Federal Communications Commissioner put it: "The country that has 5G will have the related innovations and set the standards for the rest of the world, and this country is unlikely to be the United States at the moment."
Other countries — especially the United Kingdom — have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software and hardware.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they are almost certainly capable of being shut down at that time.
The debate over Huawei is also raging in Germany, as the U.S. government threatens to cut intelligence cooperation unless authorities keep Huawei's 5G technology out.
Perhaps under U.S. pressure, the head of Germany's federal intelligence agency recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "Infrastructure is not a domain suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted."
And he was unable to provide any evidence of specific wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel is fighting behind the scenes to open the market to Huawei.
But ironically, the U.S. complaints partly reflect its own surveillance activities domestically and abroad — although this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment may make it more difficult for the U.S. government to carry out secret surveillance.
However, any government's unjustified surveillance should be stopped.
The United Nations' independent oversight to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional safeguards, rather than engage in a technological war.
The threat posed by the U.S. demand to ban Huawei extends beyond the early rollout of 5G networks and poses significant risks to the rule-based trading system.
Now the United States is no longer an uncontested global technological leader, and President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete within a rule-based system.
Their goal is to contain China's technological rise.
They are also trying to undermine the World Trade Organization by paralyzing its dispute settlement mechanism, an action that also reflects their approach to global rules.
If the Trump administration succeeds in "splitting" the world into different technological camps, the risk of future conflicts will double.
After World War II, the United States promoted open trade, which could not only improve global efficiency, expand the U.S. technology market, but also reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
The partial cause of the collapse was the protectionist tariffs imposed by the United States under the 1930 Smoot-Hull Tariff, which exacerbated the Great Depression and ultimately contributed to the rise of Hitler and the outbreak of World War II.
Just as in other areas, inciting fear and acting upon it — rather than following evidence — is a path toward destruction in international affairs.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules; this is the safest approach.
Let us establish independent monitoring bodies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to spy on other countries or launch cyber warfare.
In this way, the world can quickly harness breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
